<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>

<worksheet xml:id="coupled-system-opening">
  <exercise>
    <statement>
      <p>
        So far, we have modeled one medication concentration at a time. But many
        biological systems involve feedback. For example, one hormone level can
        influence the production or suppression of another.
      </p>

      <p>
        We now study a simplified two-variable model. Let <m>E(t)</m> represent
        an estradiol-related concentration and let <m>T(t)</m> represent a
        testosterone-related concentration.
      </p>
    </statement>
  </exercise>

  <exercise>
    <statement>
      <p>
        Consider the system
      </p>

      <me>
        \begin{aligned}
        E' \amp = -aE + u,\\
        T' \amp = b - cE - dT.
        \end{aligned}
      </me>

      <p>
        Here <m>a,b,c,d</m> are positive constants, and <m>u</m> represents a
        steady external input.
      </p>

      <p>
        Interpret each term in the model:
      </p>

      <ul>
        <li><m>-aE</m></li>
        <li><m>u</m></li>
        <li><m>b</m></li>
        <li><m>-cE</m></li>
        <li><m>-dT</m></li>
      </ul>
    </statement>
  </exercise>

  <exercise>
    <statement>
      <p>
        Rewrite the system
      </p>

      <me>
        \begin{aligned}
        E' &amp;= -aE + u,\\
        T' &amp;= b - cE - dT
        \end{aligned}
      </me>

      <p>
        in matrix form as
      </p>

      <me>\mathbf{x}' = A\mathbf{x}+\mathbf{r}</me>

      <p>
        where
      </p>

      <me>
        \mathbf{x}=
        \begin{pmatrix}
        E\\
        T
        \end{pmatrix}.
      </me>

      <p>
        Identify the matrix <m>A</m> and the vector <m>\mathbf{r}</m>.
      </p>
    </statement>
  </exercise>

  <exercise xml:id="coupled-system-equilibrium">
    <statement>
      <p>
        An equilibrium occurs when <m>E'=0</m> and <m>T'=0</m>.
      </p>

      <p>
        Solve the system
      </p>

      <me>
        \begin{aligned}
        0 \amp = -aE + u,\\
        0 \amp = b - cE - dT
        \end{aligned}
      </me>

      <p>
        to find the equilibrium point <m>(E^\ast,T^\ast)</m>.
      </p>
    </statement>
  </exercise>

  <exercise>
    <statement>
      <p>
        Suppose treatment is interrupted, so the external input changes from
        <m>u &gt; 0</m> to <m>u=0</m>.
      </p>

      <p>
        The new system is
      </p>

      <me>
        \begin{aligned}
        E' &amp;= -aE,\\
        T' &amp;= b - cE - dT.
        \end{aligned}
      </me>

      <p>
        Find the new equilibrium point.
      </p>
    </statement>
  </exercise>

  <exercise>
    <statement>
      <p>
        To make the system concrete, suppose
      </p>

      <me>a=0.4,\quad b=1.0,\quad c=0.6,\quad d=0.5.</me>

      <p>
        First assume regular treatment with <m>u=1.2</m>. Find the equilibrium
        <m>(E^\ast,T^\ast)</m>.
      </p>

      <p>
        Then assume treatment is interrupted, so <m>u=0</m>. Find the new
        equilibrium.
      </p>
    </statement>
  </exercise>

  <exercise>
    <statement>
      <p>
        The matrix for the homogeneous part of the system is
      </p>

      <me>
        A=
        \begin{pmatrix}
        -a &amp; 0\\
        -c &amp; -d
        \end{pmatrix}.
      </me>

      <p>
        Because this matrix is triangular, its eigenvalues are visible on the
        diagonal.
      </p>

      <p>
        What are the eigenvalues of <m>A</m>? What do they tell us about whether
        the system moves toward equilibrium or away from it?
      </p>
    </statement>
  </exercise>

  <exercise>
    <statement>
      <p>
        The model in this part is simplified: it uses only two variables, assumes
        constant parameters, and represents feedback with a linear term. Real
        endocrine systems are more complex.
      </p>

      <p>
        Still, the model shows that interrupting one input can affect more than
        one quantity. Explain how this changes the interpretation of a phrase like
        <q>the medication leaves the body after a few half-lives.</q>
      </p>
    </statement>
  </exercise>
</worksheet>